definition.value: An oligonucleotide used to start the reaction in a polymerase-chain reaction.
An RNA spike-in is an RNA transcript of known sequence and quantity used to calibrate measurements in RNA hybridization assays, such as DNA microarray experiments, RT-qPCR, and RNA-Seq.

A barcode is a short known DNA sequence that is added during the library preparation in order to identify the origin of the read during data analysis. This enables for example the pooling and simultaneous sequencing of different samples ("multiplexing").
The sequencing read that contains the cDNA read.
A cell type classification that is determined as result of a single-cell analysis, such as cell clustering or trajectory analysis.
A unique identifier for a single cell specimen.
A short nucleotide sequence that is added during a single cell library preparation to identify reads from an individual cell.
A unique molecular identifier (UMI) barcode is a short nucleotide sequence that is used to identify reads originating from an individual mRNA molecule.
A short nucleotide sequence that is added during a single cell library preparation to identify reads from the same sample or library.
The offset in the sequence where the cDNA read starts.
The length of the cDNA read.
The sequencing read that contains the cell barcode.
The offset in the sequence where the cell barcode starts.
The length of the cell barcode.
The offset in the sequence where the UMI barcode starts.
The sequencing read that contains the UMI barcode.
The length of the UMI barcode.
The sequencing read that contains the sample barcode.
The offset in the sequence where the sample barcode starts.
The length of the sample barcode.
A protocol describing the processes performed and equipment used to prepare a single cell nucleic acid sequencing library.
A protocol describing the equipment and procedure by which a single cell suspension is separated into individual cells in order to allow individual cell barcoding.
An oligonucleotide primer consisting of thymidine bases only. It is used to target messenger RNA molecules with poly-adenosine 3' end.
An oligonucleotide primer with random sequence.
Dilution factor of the RNA spike-in.
Quantification of the level of aldosterone in a sample
Quantification of the amount of 17-hydroxyprogesterone in a sample

Quantification of the drive to systemise, ie identifiy input-operation-output relationships in order to build, analyse or understand systems, typically quantified by administration of a standardised questionnaire such as the Systemising Quotient-Revised (SQ-R)
A quantification of ceramides.
A quantification of diglycerides.
A quantification of lysophosphatidylcholines.
A quantification of lysophosphatidylethanolamines.
A quantification of phosphatidylcholines.
A quantification of phosphatidylcholine ethers.
A quantification of phosphatidylethanolamines.
A quantification of phosphatidylethanolamine ethers.
A quantification of phosphatidylinositols.
A quantification of sterols.
Quantification of the amount of osteocalcin in a sample
Quantification of some aspect of exposure to genotoxic compounds, i.e. compounds that may cause DNA damage.
Quantification of the presence or absence of a particular viral subtype in an individual.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism as a result of a proton-pump inhibitor stimulus. Proton-pump inhibitors are a group of medications whose main action is a pronounced and long-lasting reduction of stomach acid production.

value.value: A condition affecting an unborn or newly born individual, where the perinatal period is defined in humans as commencing at 22 completed weeks (154 days) of gestation and ending seven completed days after birth. Other, broader definitions of perinatal period cover five months before birth to one month after birth.

definition.value: Quantification of the ratio of cortisol to dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) in a sample.
Quantification of the amount of dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) in a sample.
Quantification of the amount of galectin-3-binding protein in a sample.
Quantification of the amount of beta globulin in a sample.
Quantification of the amount of an inorganic ion, such as magnesium, iron or calcium, in a sample
Quantification of the degree of severity of uveal melanoma, eg by TNM staging
Quantification of the amount of oxytocin in a sample.
